Raise and fall of programming languages¶

Stackoverflow takes every year a survey from the users to different questions. I'll first take the data from latest 2019 survey to find answer on the following questions:

1) What are the languages with most change worked with this year and desired next year?

2) Are there differences in countries?

and with the survey data of 2018

3) Is the raise or fall of a language also seen in survey a year ago?

4) How good is the value LanguageDesireNextYear in comparison to the real value LanguageWorkedWith from next year?

Strange data¶

Out of this description of the few float/int columns you can see, that not all of the answers are useful. For example Age of 99 as programmer is possible, but Age of 1? Or the WorkWeekHrs: 4850 as max! One week has only 7x24 = 168 h maximun. So if we want to use this columns, you have to drop the strange data.

Generate a wordcloud for first overview¶

As a first look on the languages i will generate a wordcloud from all languages worked with and another one for languages desired for next year. I've to use an own regex, wordcloud uses r"\w[\w']+" but here we have languages like C# or HTML/CSS. So i will use r"[A-Za-z#/]+".

In [7]:
def plot_wordcloud(language, title=None):
    # all languages that one use, is in text string seperated with columns. So first generate one string, with all entries
    text = ";".join(text for text in language)
    #generate wordcloud with no collocations and with an own regex to handle e.g. C# and HTML/CSS
    wordcloud = WordCloud(collocations=False, width=2000, height=1000, max_words=1000, regexp= r"[A-Za-z#/]+",
                          background_color="white", relative_scaling=0).generate(text)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
    plt.axis("off")

    if title != None:
        plt.figtext(0.5,1, title, ha='center', 
                fontdict={'fontsize':30, 'color':  'darkred', 'fontweight':'bold'})
    plt.show()
    return wordcloud
    #wordcloud.to_file('languages_worked_with.png');

First look at the wordcloud¶

And we have also increasing candidates: Rust and Python. Let's have a closer look through data visualization.

In [10]:
def language_percent(df, language):
    """
    Function to calculate the percent language used
    Input: dataframe, language
    Output: dataframe with language, workedWith(percent), desiredNextYear(percent)
    """
    count_respondent = df.Respondent.count()
    #need to use regexp, because of 
    language_raw = r'\b{}\b'.format(language)
    language_perc = pd.DataFrame(columns=['language', 'workedWith', 'desiredNextYear'])
    
    workedWith = df[df.LanguageWorkedWith.str.contains(language_raw, regex=True)].Respondent.count() / count_respondent
    desiredNextYear = df[df.LanguageDesireNextYear.str.contains(language_raw, regex=True)].Respondent.count() / count_respondent
    language_perc = language_perc.append(pd.DataFrame(np.array([[language, workedWith, desiredNextYear]]), columns=['language', 'workedWith', 'desiredNextYear']))
    
    return language_perc
In [11]:
def plot_languages(df, country=None):
    """
    Plots a bar chart with the languages used this year, desired for next year and the difference
    could be filtered to a special country
    """
    if country is not None:
        data = df[df.Country == country]
    else:
        data = df
        
    ret = language_percent(data, 'Python')
    ret = ret.append(language_percent(data, 'C'), ignore_index=True)
    ret = ret.append(language_percent(data, 'Java'), ignore_index=True)
    ret = ret.append(language_percent(data, 'JavaScript'), ignore_index=True)
    ret = ret.append(language_percent(data, 'Rust'), ignore_index=True)

    ret= ret.set_index('language')
    # have to set astype to float64, otherwise plot raises an error
    ret = ret.astype({'workedWith':'float64', 'desiredNextYear':'float64'})
    # calculate the difference
    ret['diff'] = ret.desiredNextYear - ret.workedWith
    #ax.axhline(y=0, linewidth=0.5)

    ret.plot(kind='bar', use_index=True);
    if country is not None:
        plt.title(country)
    
    plt.axhline(y=0, linewidth=0.5);
    return ret

Python and Rust are increasing¶

Now we have proved our findings, the languages Java, Javascript and C are on the decreasing side of to be used in the future. Whereas Python and Rust are increasing, so more people wants to work with them in the next year. Interesting is in the United States and Germany, Python is increasing only a little bit, but in India there are around 20% increase for the next year. And Rust as language is in all mentioned countries increasing. Also interesting, that in India more people wants to drop C as language and in United States and Germany more people drop Java and JavaScript.

Findings¶

One obvious finding from the word cloud is, that many more languages are mentioned in 2018, not more mentioned in 2019! E.g. Cobol and Pascal. But as the languages were predefined in the survey from StackOverFlow, you cannot conlcude, that one of these languages are not more used.

The raise of python is here only in india and rust is raising in all three countries as you can see on the following plots. But in comparison to 2019, the desired languages are not raise or fall as fast as mentioned.

As expected, the wish to work or not to work with a language next year is bigger than the real world. If you see JavaScript for example, nearly 20 % wantet to don't use in the next year, but in 2019 there is only a few percent decrease in programmers, that are worked with JavaScript.

Conclusion¶

The languages used for programming in the last two years are changing. In 2018 many more languages were mentioned as in 2019, but that is coming from the survey creators. The top used languages like C, Java and Javascript are still used and not so fast decreasing as many developers desired. Especially if you compare 2018 and 2019. Another interesting finding, ist that in India most people don't want to use C in the next year, in 2018 and also in 2019. Therefore they want to use Python or Rust. Whereas in Germany and United States the developers don't want to use Java and JavaScript and Python is raising from 2019 on and not in 2018.
